## 1. Introduction: The Crisis of Extractive Simulation
The dominant technological model of the 21st century is not neutral computation; it is organized extraction. This paper defines **Extractive Simulation** as a sociotechnical system in which lived human reality is continuously converted into data, modeled into predictive abstractions, and operationalized into decisions that shape both economic opportunity and state coercion. Extractive simulation is not limited to consumer advertising. It increasingly governs employment monitoring, credit eligibility, healthcare triage, and, most urgently, criminal-legal decision-making.

Predictive policing platforms, real-time crime centers, and AI surveillance infrastructures represent the institutional maturation of extractive simulation. These systems are marketed as tools of efficiency and public safety. Yet empirical investigations and policy critiques repeatedly demonstrate low predictive accuracy, discriminatory enforcement amplification, and expansive downstream harms (The Markup, 2023; Tech Policy Press, 2024; Algorithm Watch, 2025). They may fail at prediction, but they succeed at legitimation: producing “objective” rationales for the concentration of policing and surveillance in already over-targeted communities.

Most governance discourse treats algorithmic bias as correctable through technical improvement: better datasets, more audits, more transparency. This paper argues that such approaches are necessary but structurally insufficient. Extraction systems cannot be ethically repaired through procedural fixes if their core purpose remains behavior capture and predictive control.

The solution must be systemic and enforceable at the federal level—through standards, procurement, liability, and civil rights law. The framework proposed here combines sociological diagnosis with implementable policy design.

