## 2. Theoretical Framework: Extraction as an Objective Function

### 2.1 Surveillance Capitalism and Behavioral Surplus
Surveillance capitalism describes an economic logic in which data about human behavior becomes a raw material for prediction and profit (Zuboff, 2019). The critical transformation is not “data collection” alone, but the conversion of experience into *behavioral surplus*—the excess extractable behavioral signals that can be sold as predictive products.

This logic has proven portable. It scales not only across industries but across institutions. When predictive modeling moves into governance systems, the same extraction infrastructure becomes a tool of administrative decision power.
* **In the market:** Extraction drives persuasion and behavioral influence.
* **In the state:** Extraction drives classification and coercive legitimacy.

This paper treats the carceral use-case as the clearest demonstration that surveillance capitalism is not only economic; it is political.

### 2.2 The Flattening Problem: Why Predictive Systems Require Dehumanization
Predictive systems depend on compressing complex human life into machine-legible categories. This flattening is often framed as a technical limitation. In reality, it is the core precondition for extraction-based optimization.

Humans are not stable input-output functions. Yet systems optimized for prediction require treating them as such. In doing so, these systems systematically exclude context, relationship, agency, meaning-making, and self-determined intent. Flattening therefore creates not only misclassification harms, but an ontological violence: the loss of personhood recognition within institutional decision systems.

### 2.3 Feedback Loops and Bias Amplification
Predictive policing illustrates the feedback loop problem with unusual clarity. When enforcement history is biased, then training data is biased. If the model then directs policing attention back into the same communities, the enforcement bias reproduces itself as fresh “evidence” (Human Rights Data Analysis Group, 2019; The Markup, 2023).

This dynamic transforms bias into an engine of legitimacy:
> **Biased enforcement → Biased data → Biased prediction → Biased deployment → Increased biased enforcement.**

Recent work on human–AI feedback loops suggests a deeper hazard: biased systems don’t only reproduce data errors—they can reshape human judgment over time, escalating bias through human-machine interaction (Nature, 2024).

